<subSubSection pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1437,1402,1571]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,1474,1499]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Notes.</emphasis>
A cucurbit specialist. This is an important native pollinator of cucurbit crops in Michigan (
<bibRefCitation author="Quinn" box="[1286,1425,1474,1499]" firstAuthor="Quinn" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" refId="ref99368" refString="Quinn, N. F. (2015) Habitat management for beneficial insects in Michigan cucurbit agroecosystems. MSc thesis, Michigan State University, East Lansing, Michigan, 94 pp." type="book" year="2015">Quinn 2015</bibRefCitation>
). Nests from California and Rhode Island were described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hurd" box="[814,1015,1510,1535]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hurd" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="1 - 17" refId="ref91067" refString="Hurd, P. D., Linsley, E. G. &amp; Michelbacher, A. E. (1974) Ecology of the squash and gourd bee, Peponapis pruinosa, on cultivated cucurbits in California (Hymenoptera: Apoidea). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 168, 1 - 17. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.168" type="journal article" year="1974">
Hurd 
<emphasis box="[878,934,1510,1535]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">et al.</emphasis>
(1974)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Mathewson" box="[1069,1284,1510,1535]" firstAuthor="Mathewson" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="255 - 261" refId="ref94094" refString="Mathewson, J. A. (1968) Nest construction and life history of the eastern cucurbit bee, Peponapis pruinosa (Hymenoptera: Apoidea). Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 41, 255 - 261." type="journal article" year="1968">Mathewson (1968)</bibRefCitation>
, respectively. Population genetics of the species in North America were investigated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lopez-Uribe" box="[981,1271,1546,1571]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Lopez-Uribe" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="1833" refId="ref93622" refString="Lopez-Uribe, M. M., Cane, J. H., Minckley, R. L. &amp; Danforth, B. N. (2016) Crop domestication facilitated rapid geographical expansion of a specialist pollinator, the squash bee Peponapis pruinosa. Proceedings of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences, 283 (1833). https: // doi. org / 10.1098 / rspb. 2016.0443" type="journal article" year="2016">
LÃ³pez-Uribe 
<emphasis box="[1130,1186,1546,1571]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">et al.</emphasis>
(2016)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
